```Expr``` is a base class.
The switch matches it to a specific subclass and extracts parameters from the record.  Those parameters are used in the expression for the return value of the switch expression.

So if ```n``` is an instance of ```IntExpr``` the ```int i``` member of the record is returned.
If ```n``` is a ```NegExpr``` its ```Expr n``` member is passed recursively to the ```eval``` method and then the result is negated before it is returned.
Similarly when matching an ```AddExpr``` or ```MulExpr``` the ```left``` and ```right``` Expr members are used to recursively evaluate those expressions and return the sum or the product respectively.

So each case matches a specific type with the specified fields and makes those fields available for the expression that is evaluated and returned for the value of the switch expression.

See also https://openjdk.java.net/jeps/406

This could be re-written as:

    int eval(Expr n) {
        if (n instanceof IntExp ie) {
            return ie.i;
        }
        if (n instanceof NegExpr ne) {
            return -eval(ne.e);
        }
        if (n instanceof AddExp ae) {
            return eval(ae.left) + eval(ae.right);
        }
        if (n instanceof MulExpr me) {
            return eval(me.left) * eval(me.right);
        }
        throw new IllegalArgumentException(n);
    }

