I can not reproduce your result with the [current version of your question]. Since you edited the code in a way that the problem disappeared, I have to emphasize that this is *not* the way, Stackoverflow works. Your question about a specific problem is supposed to contain the code necessary to reproduce the problem. The [*Answers*] section is dedicated to contain solutions.

Besides the original problem of not calling `setAccessible` on the second `Field` instance, it’s not clear why you are using a second `Field` object in the first place.

There are two possible scenarios.

 1. You assume both objects to have the same type. Then, there is no reason to operate with two arrays of `Field` objects. You can just use one array to access both objects.

 2. You assume that the objects may have different types. Then it is entirely unreasonable to assume that the two arrays of `Field` objects of different classes correspond in any way.

In fact, [the documentation of `getDeclaredFields()`] specifies

&gt; The elements in the returned array are not sorted and are not in any particular order.

and does not even state that calling `getDeclaredFields()` twice on the same `Class` object will return fields in the same order.

You should use your approach only for objects of the same type and just use one array of fields. When descending to objects contained in fields, use `equals` where appropriate, as certain types (e.g. collections) have equality rules for objects of different implementation classes.

For example

```java
static boolean equalByMemberFields(Object obj1, Object obj2)
                                                throws ReflectiveOperationException {

    if(obj1 == obj2) return true;
    else if(obj1 == null || obj2 == null) return false;

    Class&lt;?&gt; objClass1 = obj1.getClass();
    if(obj2.getClass() != objClass1) return false;

    Field[] fields = objClass1.getDeclaredFields();
    AccessibleObject.setAccessible(fields, true); // on all at once

    for(Field field : fields) {
        Object value1 = field.get(obj1), value2 = field.get(obj2);
        if(shouldDescend(field.getType())) {
            if( ! equalByMemberFields(value1, value2)) return false;
        } else {
            System.out.println(&quot;Field: &quot; + field.getName()
                + &quot;, value1: &quot; + value1 + &quot;, value2: &quot; + value2);

            if(!Objects.equals(value1, value2)) return false;
        }
    }
    return true;
}

private static boolean shouldDescend(Class&lt;?&gt; type) throws NoSuchMethodException {

    if(type.isPrimitive() || type.isEnum()) return false;

    if(type.getClassLoader() == null) return false; // don&#39;t peek into core classes

    if(type.getMethod(&quot;equals&quot;, Object.class).getDeclaringClass() != Object.class)
        return false; // has overridden equals method

    return true;
}
```

